passages.text: Overall comment: Underlying NPAT 2H25 was very slightly softer than expected driven by Better group insurance margin at \(17.8\%\) vs. consensus of \(17.6\%\) (largely from non- resident business) but this was offset by higher expenses which was slightly above the top end of FY25 guidance of \(\) 650\(m and lower MPL Health profits. The margin expansion coming through from resident was in line but driven by better - than - expected risk equalisation outcomes. 2H25 claims inflation improved to 2.1% vs. 1H25 of 2.3% with guidance of 2.6% to 2.9% for FY26 (based on agreed FY25 indexation against rate of - 4% for the most part of FY26 suggesting perhaps margin stability into FY26).

1) Underlying NPAT: 2H25 result was a small miss at A\(320.0m vs. GSe of A\)325.2m and MPL consensus of A\(329.5m. 2) Group operating profit: 2H25 result was a small miss at A\)402.3m vs. GSe of A\(408.9m and MPL consensus of A\)404.6m. 3) Dividend in line with MPL's payout ratio: Dividend per share of 10.2cps vs. GSe of 10.0cps (MPL consensus 10.2cps). Payout ratio for 2H25 was \(\sim 88\%\) , FY25 payout ratio was 80% vs. 75-85% target of underlying NPAT. 4) Health insurance operating profit - broadly in line: 2H25 was at A\)392m vs. GSe at A\(394m (MPL consensus A\)392m). 5) Medibank Health - slightly softer: 2H25 MPL Health segment profit was weaker than expected at A\)39.1m vs. GSe of A\)43.9m and MPL consensus at A\)42.2m. 6) Underlying resident gross margin was in line at 16.9% for 2H25 vs. GSe of 16.9% (MPL consensus 16.9%). Net margin in line at 9.5%.

Net resident policyholder growth of \(1.4\%\) for FY25 and aims to grow market share in FY26 (further growth in MPL brand): MPL brand up \(0.3\%\) and AHM up \(4.3\%\) - MPL flags improving momentum over 2H25. Downgrading quite high, a similar trend to NHF - MPL expects higher downgrading in FY26; customer growth skewed to lower tier products: \(0.9\%\) for FY25 suggesting \(1.3\%\) for 2H25. Lapse rate improved between 2024 and 2025: Investment in additional product benefit. Claims per policy unit booked at \(2.1\%\) vs. midpoint of assumption at \(2.7\%\) : Exports claims per policy unit growth of \(2.6 - 2.9\%\) over FY26. Non- resident business: Policyholder growth of \(11.6\%\) in FY25 vs. pcp driven by

positive momentum in worker acquisitions, student acquisition was impacted by lower visa approvals. Gross margin also was at \(36.9\%\) for FY25 (+270bps on pcp). MPL will invest to grow market share in FY26, particularly in worker and visitor segments.

Medibank Health: 2H25 MPL Health segment profit was weaker than expected at \(A\) 39.1m vs. GSe of \(A\) 43.9m and MPL consensus at \(A\) 42.2m. Gross margin in MPL Health (excluding MyHealth) contracted by 110bps to \(52.8\%\) in FY25 vs. pcp whilst net margin increased 100bps to \(19.1\%\) , reflecting improved MER efficiency and operating leverage. Myhealth operating profit was \(A\) 10.5m over 2H25 vs. \(A\) 11.6m in 2H24. MPL continues to target \(>15\%\) per annum organic growth and M&A investment towards the top end of the \(A\) 150m to \(A\) 250m range over FY24- FY26 (3 years), with \(\sim A\) 59m invested in FY24 and FY25.

MPL had a pre tax covid reserve of \(\) 228m\(as at Dec - 24, with a declared giveback of\) \ \(228m\) announced, 2H25 savings of \(\sim A\) 30m were allocated to Live Better give- backs: Based on MPL's commitment to return all permanent claims savings from Covid to customers. However we note that there was a material increase in the LIC over 1H25 to 2H25.

Capital position strong at PCA ratio of \(1.8x\) and Capital ratio at \(14.0\%\) , above target range of \(10 - 12\%\) (additional capital held to offset APRA supervisory adjustment) and unallocated capital of \(A\) 186.2m. MPL remains open to capital management if suitable M&A opportunities do not eventuate and expects to deploy \(\sim A\) 150- 250m between FY24 and FY26 for M&A with opportunity to raise Tier 2 capital as well. We await an update of when MPL's APRA capital over lay of \(A\) 250m is removed.

Investment income: for 2H25 was at \(A\) 93.3m vs. GSe of \(A\) 90.6m (MPL consensus \(A\) 93.3m). Underlying spread to RBA cash rate was 166bps (vs. 150- 200bps spread targeted). MPL expects 25bps rate cuts to impact annualised interest income by \(\) 7m\(. MPL will consider options including target asset allocation and defensive asset settings to help offset RBA cash rate impacts.

Focus on sustainable and disciplined growth- Further improve retention, particularly in a high through further digital investment and integrated customer propositions- Disciplined growth in priority segments, including the growing corporate segment- Deepen brand differentiation with investment in new products and services
Industry growth: anticipate moderating industry growth relative to FY25
Policyholder growth: aim to grow market share in a disciplined way, including further volume growth in the Medibank brand

Proactive claims management strategy to mitigate inflationary pressures on claims- Broaden successful partnership approach to hospital contracting- Increase number of Medibank customers supported by personalised models of care- Expand use of artificial intelligence in payment integrity program
Claims: expect claims per policy unit growth of \(2.6\% - 2.9\%\)
Continuing focus on students, with increasing focus in worker and visitor segments- Lifecycle management opportunity for customers who become Australian residents
Gross profit: aim to maintain solid gross profit growth
Further performance uplift in healthcare services- Meet the needs of more of our existing health insurance customers- Opportunity to scale existing programs to a broader set of payors
Medibank Health: expect low double- digit organic operating profit growth
Augment Medibank Health's organic growth with further M&A

Target investments that add scale, capability and expand geographic coverage- Near- term focus on expanding primary and virtual care footprint and broadening participation in fast growing corporate health & wellbeing sector
M&A: based on the strong asset pipeline, we aim to invest towards the top end of the \$150m - \$250m FY24 - FY26 M&A target where this creates long- term value
Source: Company data
Resident policyholder growth: MPL aims to gain share from FY26. MPL expects industry growth to moderate in FY26 vs. FY25.

Resident policyholder market share: MPL continues to target Resident policyholder market share growth of \(25 - 75\) bps by FY27 on FY24 (Jun- 24 market share was \(26.70\%\) , but Jun- 25 market share dropped to \(26.46\%\) ).

- Policyholder giveback / Covid-19 equity reserve: MPL has finalised the giveback program with the giveback increased to A\(228m from A\)160m. As at Jun-25, Covid-19 reserve balance was now fully released.- Claims inflation expectations: MPL now targets claims per policy unit growth of 2.6% to 2.9% for FY26 across resident business (FY25 was 2.2%).- Downgrading: increased in FY25 to 0.9%, expects modestly higher downgrading in FY26.- Expenses: MPL targets a stable to modestly improving MER (was 8.0% over FY25). MPL again guides to A\(10m of productivity savings over FY26 (vs. A\)10m in FY25).- Cybercrime costs: MPL expects cybercrime costs of \~A\(35m for FY26 (FY25 was A\)39.7m) but continues to exclude cost of potential findings or regulatory outcomes or litigations. FY27 costs expected to be largely related to regulatory investigations and litigation.- Medibank Health: MPL continues to target >15% per annum organic growth and M&A investment towards the top end of the A\)150m to A\(250m range over FY24-FY26 (3 years), with \~A\)59m invested in FY24 and FY25.- Dividend payout range of 75%-85% of Underlying NPAT maintained.- Non-resident: Will invest to grow market share in FY26, particularly in worker and visitor segments.

MPL is one of the largest private health insurers in Australia. We have a relative Neutral rating on the stock. We like MPL given: 1) It offers defensive exposure to the private health insurance sector 2) The claims environment (utilisation / inflation) has been broadly benign but with evidence of inflation / hospital indexation, 3) policyholder give backs are supporting retention. We are Neutral rated largely reflecting MPL's strong valuation.

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.
